Introduction:

Control Overfitting of Linear Regressions using Regularization

Problem with overfitted machine learning models.

  • Overfitting in machine learning describes a model that has learned the training data so well (including the noise in the data) that it only "knows" the training data, and cannot generalize well to new data.

  • The meme below is a funny and abstract way to think of overfitting. If your bed adjusted to how you slept once, then it would be a terrible bed to sleep in because you will not always sleep in the same position.

  • Overfitted models are similar, in that they learn all the nuance and variation in the training data, and as a result, cannot properly adjust to new data.

  • As a result, overfit models:
    • have low accuracy
    • are "too" complex for their own good
    • have high variance (aka too sensitive to small variations in the training data)

  • There are several approaches that can be used to avoid overfitting:
    • Cross validation
    • Regularization

  • Linear regression regularization constrains the model by adjusting the weights of the model.

  • The three most common methods of linear model regularization include:
    • Ridge Regression
    • Lasso Regression
    • Elastic Net Regression

The goal of this post is to demonstrate how to avoid overfitting by using Lasso Regularization.

Plot Polynomial Regression for Select Boston Housing Data Features

In [7]:
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))

features = ['CRIM', 'NOX', 'RM', 'AGE', 'TAX', 'LSTAT']
y = pd.DataFrame(boston.target)

for i, col in enumerate(features):
    plt.subplot(2, 3, i+1)    
    x = dataframe[col]
    
    # polynomial regression
    poly_features = PolynomialFeatures(degree=10, include_bias=False)
    X_poly = poly_features.fit_transform(np.c_[x])
    lin_reg = LinearRegression()
    lin_reg.fit(X_poly, y)
    lin_reg.intercept_, lin_reg.coef_
    
    # plot set-up
    X_new = np.linspace(0, x.max(), 100).reshape(100, 1)
    X_new_poly = poly_features.transform(X_new)
    # predict y from the data
    y_new = lin_reg.predict(X_new_poly)
    
    # plot polynomial curve
    plt.plot(X_new, y_new, "r-", linewidth=2, label="Predictions")

    # scatter plot of data
    plt.scatter(x, y, marker='o')
    plt.title(col)
    plt.xlabel(col)
    plt.ylabel('MEDV')
    plt.tight_layout()
Comments:
  • Each model overfits the data by capturing too much of the variation.

  • These models have high variance and will not generalize well with new data.

Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator Regression (Lasso Regression)

  • A regularized version of Linear Regression

  • Uses the first norm of the weight vector instead of half the square of the norm 2 that is used in Ridge regression

  • A hyperparameter alpha is added to the cost function.

  • The added hyperparameter alpha term forces the learning algorithm to fit the data and keep the model weights as small as possible.

  • If the hyperparameter alpha = 0, then the regression is just a simple Linear Regression.

  • If the hyperparameter alpha is large, then all weights end up very close to zero, and a flat line will go through the data's mean.

  • Lasso Regression tends to completely eliminate the weights of the least important features and sets it to zero.

  • Lasso Regression automatically performs feature selection and outputs a model with few nonzero feature weights.

  • The regulaziation term is only added to the cost function during the training step.

  • The performance of the model is then conducted using the unregularized method.

  • The data would need to be scaled before performing regularization regression, as this method is sensitive to the scale of the input features.

  1. PolynomialFeatures(degree=n)

  2. input data is scaled using a StandardScaler

  3. Apply model to the resulting features

  4. Test model on new data

# step one import dependencies
from sklearn.linear_model import Lasso

# Room Feature
X = np.c_[dataframe['RM']]

# Target data (median household price)
y = pd.DataFrame(boston.target).values

# standardize data, an essential step in regularization
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaler.fit(X)

# carry out regression with alpha = 0 and using closed form
lasso_reg = Lasso(alpha=0.1)
lasso_reg.fit(X, y)

# Test model with 5 rooms. 
# The predicted MEDV is nearly 11 (standardsized)
lasso_reg.predict([[5]])

Visual Explanation on Lasso Regression Mechanics

In [12]:
def plot_model(dataframe, feature, y, model_class, polynomial, alphas, **model_kargs):
    X = np.c_[dataframe[feature]]
    X_new = np.linspace(0, X.max(), 100).reshape(100, 1) #.reshape converts to 2d array
    for alpha, style in zip(alphas, ("b-", "g--", "r:")):
        model = model_class(alpha, **model_kargs) if alpha > 0 else LinearRegression()
        if polynomial:
            model = Pipeline([
                    ("poly_features", PolynomialFeatures(degree=10, include_bias=False)),
                    ("std_scaler", StandardScaler()),
                    ("regul_reg", model),
                ])
        model.fit(X, y)
        y_new_regul = model.predict(X_new)
        lw = 2 if alpha > 0 else 1
        plt.plot(X_new, y_new_regul, style, linewidth=lw, label=r"$\alpha = {}$".format(alpha))
    plt.plot(X, y, "b.", linewidth=3)
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", fontsize=15)
    plt.xlabel(f"{feature}", fontsize=18)
    plt.ylabel("MEDV", fontsize=18)
    x_max = X.max()*1.1
    y_max = y.max()*1.1
    plt.axis([0, x_max, 0, y_max])
    plt.tight_layout()

Comments

  • Lasso regression eliminates the weight of the least important features and sets them to zero.

  • In the regression above, the number of rooms feature was tested with the Median value of owner-occupied homes in boston.

  • In the linear regression (left panel), small introduction of the alpha regularization made little impact on the regression curve, although increasing it's magniture to 1 reduced the model overfitting.

  • In the polynomial regression (right panel), by increasing the alpha hyperparameter by 0.1 (dashed green line) nearly completely removed the quadratic features of the curve in blue (hyperparameter = 0).
